text: Your team is designing a battery pack for a Formula Student competition. The simulation team calculated that with derating ensuring optimal results in the Endurance event, you will need to use a total sum of 5.334 kWh of energy.\n You are considering using three different cylindrical cells for your battery, and you are trying to judge which cell and pack configuration is the most optimal to use for your Formula Student race car. Your design criteria are: total weight of the cells, gravimetric energy density, gravimetric power density and compliance to the latest FS rules.\n  Which of the proposed cell, segment, pack configurations is best optimized according to these criteria?

answer_options.answer_text: Cell A: 5 segments connected in series; single segment configuration 28S3P

Cell C: 8 segments connected in series; single segment configuration 18S1P

answers.answer_text: Cell A: 5 segments connected in series; single segment configuration 28S3P

text:
Two teams are competing in Skid Pad Event on FSP 2024, they have their second run. Both vehicles are running in the middle of the track. 
 - Car A has average coefficient of friction on both circles µA=1,32 [-], car B has average coefficient of friction on right circle µBr=1,51 [-] and on left circle µBl=1,27 [-]. 
 - Both vehicles have their maximum speed in steady state conditions and have full contact patch with the track. 
 - Which team is faster and what is the final run time difference according to procedure between those teams after finish Skid Pad event. 
 - Assume that aerodynamic resistance and downforce are negligible and g=9,81 m/sec^2.
 Round the calculations and answer to hundredths.

answer_options.answer_text: Both teams have the same time

answers.answer_text: Both teams have the same time
